From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: pai-nix <pai-nix@localhost>
Date: Sun, 3 May 2026 17:30:00 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 18/18] Emit step_skip event for every Telegram skip path

Upstream issue: danielmiessler/Personal_AI_Infrastructure (TBD)

In the v5.0 GUI installer, runTelegramSetup() in
PAI/PAI-Install/engine/actions.ts has five skip paths
(user-skipped / no-token-entered / invalid-token /
no-allowed-users / env-write-failed). Each one calls a
file-local skipStep() helper that mutates state.skippedSteps
in memory but never emits the corresponding `step_skip`
EngineEvent. The web installer's WebSocket bridge in
web/routes.ts:71-72 listens for that event and only then
broadcasts `{ type: "step_update", step: "telegram", status:
"skipped" }` to the browser.

Net effect: the user picks "Skip Telegram", the engine moves
on, validation runs, and the install completes — but step 8
stays highlighted "active" in the GUI sidebar forever, while
the bottom-right "INSTALLATION COMPLETE" banner is rendered.
The two states contradict each other on screen and the user
reasonably interprets the install as broken.

This patch keeps the local skipStep helper (its in-memory
mutation is still needed by the outer flow's
`if (!state.skippedSteps.includes(...))` guards), but adds
an `await emit({ event: "step_skip", step: "telegram",
reason })` call immediately before each skipStep(...) call
so the GUI receives the step transition at the moment the
engine records it. The leading "Skipped Telegram setup..."
message stays — it's the human-readable assistant message,
distinct from the structured step_skip event.

The same architectural shape exists in runVoiceSetup (skip
paths there don't emit step_skip either) but voice's skip
path is mostly handled by routes.ts's catch block which
calls the engine's exported skipStep — and the user-visible
symptom doesn't manifest there because voice's UI behavior
masks it. Telegram is the visible victim because skipping
it is a deliberate, common user choice. A broader sweep
across all step runners is left for a follow-up; this patch
fixes the bug the user reported.

The comment block on the local skipStep helper is updated
to document the caller-emits-event contract so the next
person to touch this code doesn't reintroduce the bug by
adding a sixth skip path that forgets the emit.
---
 .claude/PAI/PAI-Install/engine/actions.ts | 18 +++++++++++++++---
 1 file changed, 15 insertions(+), 3 deletions(-)

--- a/Releases/v5.0.0/.claude/PAI/PAI-Install/engine/actions.ts
+++ b/Releases/v5.0.0/.claude/PAI/PAI-Install/engine/actions.ts
@@ -2245,6 +2245,7 @@

   if (wantsTelegram !== "yes") {
     await emit({ event: "message", content: "Skipped Telegram setup. Add later: TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN and TELEGRAM_ALLOWED_USERS in ~/.claude/.env, then bash ~/.claude/PAI/PULSE/manage.sh restart" });
+    await emit({ event: "step_skip", step: "telegram", reason: "user-skipped" });
     skipStep(state, "telegram", "user-skipped");
     return;
   }
@@ -2301,6 +2302,7 @@
     const trimmed = entered.trim();
     if (!trimmed) {
       await emit({ event: "message", content: "No token entered. Skipping Telegram setup." });
+      await emit({ event: "step_skip", step: "telegram", reason: "no-token-entered" });
       skipStep(state, "telegram", "no-token-entered");
       return;
     }
@@ -2308,6 +2310,7 @@
     const result = await validateTelegramBotToken(trimmed);
     if (!result.valid) {
       await emit({ event: "message", content: `Token validation failed: ${result.error}. Skipping Telegram setup.` });
+      await emit({ event: "step_skip", step: "telegram", reason: "invalid-token" });
       skipStep(state, "telegram", "invalid-token");
       return;
     }
@@ -2330,6 +2333,7 @@
   }
   if (!allowedUsers) {
     await emit({ event: "message", content: "No allowed user/chat ID provided. Bot will not respond to anyone (unsafe). Skipping." });
+    await emit({ event: "step_skip", step: "telegram", reason: "no-allowed-users" });
     skipStep(state, "telegram", "no-allowed-users");
     return;
   }
@@ -2346,6 +2350,7 @@
     await emit({ event: "message", content: "Telegram credentials written to ~/.claude/.env." });
   } catch (err: any) {
     await emit({ event: "message", content: `Could not write .env: ${err?.message || err}. Telegram bot will not start.` });
+    await emit({ event: "step_skip", step: "telegram", reason: "env-write-failed" });
     skipStep(state, "telegram", "env-write-failed");
     return;
   }
@@ -2363,8 +2368,15 @@
   await emit({ event: "step_complete", step: "telegram" });
 }

-// Helper used by runTelegramSetup. Local re-export shim to avoid touching the
-// generic skip flow up top — the runners already handle skippedSteps.
+// Helper used by runTelegramSetup. Mutates state.skippedSteps so the outer
+// install flow's `if (!state.skippedSteps.includes(...))` guards observe
+// the skip. Step-skip EVENT emission (which drives UI updates in the web
+// installer) is the caller's responsibility — every callsite in
+// runTelegramSetup pairs `skipStep(...)` with a preceding
+// `await emit({ event: "step_skip", step: "telegram", reason })`. Without
+// the emit, the engine mutates state but the GUI never receives the
+// step transition, leaving step 8 highlighted "active" indefinitely
+// even though the engine has moved on to validation.
 function skipStep(state: InstallState, step: StepId, _reason: string): void {
   if (!state.skippedSteps.includes(step)) state.skippedSteps.push(step);
 }
